@article{Emerson2015,
abstract = {Autocorrelation is a universal feature of spatial ecological data and has been the subject of many highly cited review and methods papers in the ecological literature (Legendre and Fortin 1989, Legendre 1993, Koenig 1999, Diniz-Filho et al. 2003, Ives and Zhu 2006, Dormann et al. 2007, Beale et al. 2010). Variables of ecological interest frequently exhibit patterns of spatial similarity or relatedness. Measurements from geograph-ically close samples tend to have similar values or are at least influenced by one another. Related values compli-cate the assumption of independence in many statistical models, including linear regression (Legendre 1993). Ignoring the autocorrelation between related observa-tions can lead to incorrect inference (e.g., inaccurate P values, confidence intervals without the desired coverage probability, and rejection of the null hypothesis at rates differing from the nominal significance level). In partic-ular, when there is positive spatial autocorrelation in the errors of a linear model, there can be substantial inflation of Type I errors. Variables that have no effect on the outcome of interest may appear highly significant with artificially narrow confidence intervals. Therefore, ac-counting for spatial autocorrelation in widely used linear models is an important topic in the ecological literature. On the subject of this topic, a recent article by Helene Wagner (Wagner 2013; hereafter Wagner) proposed an original method of addressing autocorrelation in linear regression models. Termed spatial component regression (SCR), the method combines ordinary least squares (OLS) analysis with an ordination to identify and remove spatial patterns in the residuals. The ideas developed in SCR innovatively build upon earlier work using spatial weights as one way to model spatial autocorrelation either for use in inference or to reduce potential bias (Legendre 1993). We commend Wagner's exploration of the topic and synthesis of an impressive breadth of both novel and established methodology. However, in this response we demonstrate that SCR as proposed by Wagner does not provide a solution to the inferential challenges presented by spatial autocorrelation. Through simulation, we describe several examples where SCR will actually worsen the problem. The primary concern with autocorrelation in a statistical modeling context is its effect on inference. Therefore the goal of a method designed to address autocorrelation should be to improve the performance of inferential procedures. In general, SCR uniformly fails to control the Type I error rate in situations where it is inflated by spatial autocorre-lation. Complicating the method further, the results of SCR are highly dependent upon the choice of a spatial weights matrix describing the geographic similarity between observations. Model selection for any given problem is tricky and should be based on the system being examined and potential explanatory variables. Model selection procedures should be prespecified to the extent possible to preserve inferential reliability. However, the selection process for the SCR spatial weights matrix for any given problem is ambiguous. This is a serious concern because different matrices can lead to dramatically different results, and there is potential for significant selection bias in the choice of spatial weights matrix. Wagner presented a numeric example using a single small simulated data set and an analysis of a well-known data set, but did not attempt to assess the performance of SCR through extensive simulation. Multiple experi-ments consisting of a variety of simulated data sets are needed to assess the impact SCR has upon inference. We add our comment to broadly test the SCR methodology. This comment is a summary of the results of a range of simulation experiments designed to assess the following objectives: (Q1) Inference under the null hypothesis. When a predictor of interest has no effect on the outcome, how frequently will we achieve a significant result at the nominal level a? If inference using a given method (OLS or SCR, for example) is correct, we should reject the null hypothesis at rate a. However, spatial autocorrelation can erroneously increase the apparent significance of spatial predictors and lead to an excess of Type I errors. (Q2) Inference when the predictor of interest does have an effect on the outcome. Do confidence intervals for the coefficient of a predictor of interest contain the true value at the desired rate of (1 {\`{A}} a)?},
